A phrase is a palindrome if, after converting all uppercase letters into lowercase letters and removing all non-alphanumeric characters, it reads the same forward and backward. Alphanumeric characters include letters and numbers.

s = "A man, a plan, a canal: Panama"
clean = "".join(ch.lower() for ch in s if ch.isalnum())

lowercase because 'A' != 'a'
only alphanumeric
original string untouched

A1)
clean="".join(x.lower() for x in s if x.isalnum())
        reverse=clean[::-1]
        return clean==reverse

A2)
cleaned = ''.join(filter(str.isalnum, s.lower()))
return cleaned == cleaned[::-1]


Version 1
clean = "".join(x.lower() for x in s if x.isalnum())
What happens per character x:
Check if x is alphanumeric
If yes → lowercase it → keep it
This produces:
only alphanumeric characters
all in lowercase
This is correct for the palindrome problem.

Version 2
clean = "".join(x for x in s if x.lower().isalnum())
What happens per character:
Lowercase x
Check if that lowercase version is alphanumeric
If yes → append the original x, not the lowercase one
That means:
Uppercase letters stay uppercase
You never actually normalize case
Example:
s = "Aa"
Version 1:
"a" + "a" → "aa"

Version 2:
"A" + "a" → "Aa"
Palindrome check:
"Aa" == "aA" → False
